    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3824345540" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3824345540" />
    <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera"><img alt="Inderjit Sanghera" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564826235p2/900800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3824345540?book_show_action=true">Feb 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Inderjit Sanghera" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera">Inderjit Sanghera</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3824345540" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10111374769551398813">Alexievich’s powerful dissection of the horror of wars is told via the recollections of various women who took part in the war, as drivers, as snipers, as dissidents and nurses, as mothers, wives and daughters, as people who are caught up in a whirlpool of endless violence and vitriol, as they slowly feel not only the last vestiges of their humanity being stripped away, but also their pre-conception of what it means to be a woman. Perhaps the strongest element of the book is how Alexievich depic</span>
  <span id="freeText10111374769551398813" style="display:none">Alexievich’s powerful dissection of the horror of wars is told via the recollections of various women who took part in the war, as drivers, as snipers, as dissidents and nurses, as mothers, wives and daughters, as people who are caught up in a whirlpool of endless violence and vitriol, as they slowly feel not only the last vestiges of their humanity being stripped away, but also their pre-conception of what it means to be a woman. Perhaps the strongest element of the book is how Alexievich depicts the women as driving the narrative, rather than being passive actors, quite often, especially when it comes to war, women are relegated to the periphery, are seen as weak and submissive, yet most of the women interviewed as part of the book demonstrate a sense of purpose and strength, whether it be volunteering to go on the front despite the many dangers it presents, their ability to challenge conventions by volunteering to take part in the combat, or the quiet perseverance they demonstrate through the trials and tribulations they continuously face.<br /><br />Yet it would be reductive to read the novel as purely about the role of women in war, instead Alexievich dissects the nature of war itself, with its ability to reduce men to their most violent, debased and brutish tendencies and how it ends up extinguishing not just the lives of so many people, but also all of the things which make us human. It is a irony which is perhaps not lost on the women interviewed as part of the book that in saving humanity they invariably lost some of their own. The spectre of the Second World War still haunts the modern world, yet few book explore it as directly as Alexievich does in ‘The Unwomanly Face of War’. As she notes in her preface, the disparate accounts of war provided by the women she interviews eventually coalesce into a single narrative, a narrative of pain and suffering from which a few slender beams of light sometimes shine out.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10111374769551398813" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


